and exchange, revealing the ways in which these robust social institutions are transformed by an encompassing capitalist economy. Many passenger women assert that they have been treated "olsem maket" (like market goods) by their husbands and natal kin, and they respond by fleeing home and defiantly appropriating their sexuality for their own purposes. Experiences of rape, violence, and the failure of kin to redress such wrongs figure prominently in their own stories about becoming "wayward." Drawing on village court cases, hospital records, and women's own raw, caustic , and darkly funny narratives, Wayward Women provides a riveting portrait of the way modernity engages with gender to produce new and contested subjectivities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBride pricexPapua New GuineaxTari District. 0aBride pricezPapua New GuineazTari District. 0aCourtshipxPapua New GuineaxTari District. 0aCourtshipzPapua New GuineazTari District. 0aWomen, HulixEconomic conditionsxPapua New GuineaxTari District. 0aWomen, HulixSexual behaviorxPapua New GuineaxTari District. 0aWomen, HulixSexual behaviorzPapua New GuineazTari District. 0aWomen, HulixSocial conditionsxPapua New GuineaxTari District. 0aWomen, HulizPapua New GuineazTari DistrictxEconomic conditions. 0aWomen, HulizPapua New GuineazTari DistrictxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938977423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520938977.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC